ajit_sjc\r\n\r\n\r\n--089e01634eeefd829d04f4b9a2f9\r\nContent-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1\r\n\r\nDear Kannan,\n\n&gt;   &quot;Aatma just exists and nothing else exists&quot; ... Yes. Very Good.\n&gt;  &quot;Aatma has a center of desire. The ability to have the desire is a\npermanent nature of Aatma&quot; ... Yes. Very Good. Aatma has Chitta where\ninfinite latent vrittis are in a seed form.\n&gt; &quot;When Aatma is not in the &#39;desire&#39; form. It is in the state of Moksha&quot;\n... Yes. Very Good. Moksha is basically realizing one&#39;s true nature. Once\nAatma realizes its true nature, and gets freedom from Avidya or ignorance,\nit is Moksha indeed.\n\n\nYou seem to be trying to explain the advaita position. If this is true, you\nare either misstating the position, or are using words with your own\ndefinitions (eg. chitta).\n\nFor others in the thread -- if you wish to read a &quot;summary&quot; of the advaita\nposition, you can read the following link -- -\nhttp://www.vedantaadvaita.org/\n\nsasneham,\n\n    ajit\n\n\n\n\nOn Sat, Mar 15, 2014 at 5:37 PM, Kannan Iyengar &lt;\nprof.kannan.iyengar@...&gt; wrote:\n\n&gt;\n&gt;\n&gt;  Namasttay Shri Phil Stinnet ji and Everyone,\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]*\n&gt; *Sun 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:] *Very beautiful article.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Kannan:] *Thanks for your kind appreciation.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]*\n&gt; *Sun 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:] *\n&gt; If i understood it correctly, here is the summary -\n&gt; 1) Aatma has various names e.g. self, supreme being, para brahman,\n&gt; consciousness, existence, chaitanya or awareness.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Kannan:] *Aatma does not have any name. Name accompanies form. As Aatma\n&gt; is beyond any form, space or time, it does not have any name. Gnyaanis call\n&gt; it ParaBrahma, Yogis call it Aatma, Muslims call it Allah, Christian call\n&gt; it Father in Heaven. These names are given by us. Aatma on its own is\n&gt; nameless. Yet it is our problem that we need to call it or mention it with\n&gt; some name for our discussion.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]* *Sun\n&gt; 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:]*\n&gt;\n&gt; 2) Aatma just exists and nothing else exists.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Kannan:] *Yes. Very Good. Whatever we see in this world is Aatma in\n&gt; form and name. But it is still Aatma. Like for example, we see a golden\n&gt; bangle. What exist? Gold? Or bangle? If I melt the bangle, it becomes a\n&gt; lump of gold. So technically a bangle is a gold with a format. So this\n&gt; world we see is Aatma in a format. What exists without format is Aatma,\n&gt; What exists with format is Aatma again. This is the true tatva-gnyaana that\n&gt; Gnyaanis see. Avidya causes to see bangle in gold. And cry for bangle, when\n&gt; it loses its format and becomes a lump of gold. They become happy when\n&gt; bangle is formed out of gold and sad when bangle is dismantled back to\n&gt; gold. But there never existed any bangle before. So how it can exist now?\n&gt; It is the gold which is existing throughout.\n&gt;\n&gt; Thus the &quot;existence&quot; of this world is only in mind or imagination, not in\n&gt; absolute sense. In absolute sense, nothing exists other than Aatma.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]* *Sun\n&gt; 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:]*\n&gt;\n&gt; 3) Aatma has a center of desire. The ability to have the desire is a\n&gt; permanent nature of Aatma.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Kannan:] *Yes. Very Good. Aatma has Chitta where infinite latent\n&gt; vrittis are in a seed form. To manifest itself from one to many during\n&gt; Srushti or Creation, and to squeeze itself from many to one, during pralaya\n&gt; or dissolution, is like breathing for Aatma. It cannot avoid this. It is\n&gt; its permanent nature. It is its defining characteristics. There is no\n&gt; reason for this, As it is beyond any cause-effect rule. This feature is\n&gt; like an Axiom which cannot be proven with a precedence, because in order to\n&gt; prove, we need a statement which is already proved. And to prove that one,\n&gt; we need another precedence statement, so ultimately we need to start any\n&gt; proof with an Axiom which on its own is proofless or does not require a\n&gt; proof. This is how Maths and Science are studied. Every subject has an\n&gt; Axiom. We cannot go on endlessly proving every statement.\n&gt;\n&gt; For example, in geometry, the first axiom defined by Euclid is &quot; A point\n&gt; is something which cannot be measured and has no dimension.&quot; Now, you\n&gt; cannot expect Euclid to prove this. Because these are Axioms. I hope it is\n&gt; clear.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]* *Sun\n&gt; 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:]*\n&gt;\n&gt; 4) When Aatma has manifested itself in its &#39;desire&#39; form. It remains in\n&gt; the three states - Waking, Dreaming, Sleeping.\n&gt; Yes. Very Good.It witnesses all these states.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]* *Sun\n&gt; 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:]*\n&gt;\n&gt; 5) When Aatma is not in the &#39;desire&#39; form. It is in the state of Moksha.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Kannan:] *Yes. Very Good. Moksha is basically realizing one&#39;s true\n&gt; nature. Once Aatma realizes its true nature, and gets freedom from Avidya\n&gt; or ignorance, it is Moksha indeed. In that case, Aatma dwells without\n&gt; forming any further vrittis out of avidya or ignorance, and burns it\n&gt; remaining vrittis either though lifetimes or through the Grace of Guru\n&gt; Agni, which burns all vrittis. Without the Grace-Agni of Guru, burning of\n&gt; vrittis is nearly impossible because there are infinite vrittis, and one\n&gt; has to take infinite lifetimes to drain or discharge them out, and in that\n&gt; process if one commits or creates another vrittis, then the process is\n&gt; endless.\n&gt;\n&gt; Shrimach-Shankara-BhagavatPaada sang &quot;Punarapi Janamam, Punarapi Maranam,\n&gt; Punarapi Jananey Jatharey Shayanam,\n&gt;                                                                 &quot;Iha\n&gt; Sansaara, Bahu-Dustaara, Krupaya Paarey, Paahi Muraarey&quot;\n&gt;\n&gt; Meaning, &quot;Again I take birth, Again I die, Again I sleep in womb of my\n&gt; mother. This cycle of repeated lifetime is very intriguing and complicated,\n&gt; Oh Muraari, please ferry me across this bottomless ocean of repeated\n&gt; lifetimes.&quot;\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]* *Sun\n&gt; 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:]*\n&gt; Indeed it is a beautifully written article. I have few questions -\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Kannan:] *Thanks again for your kind and well-meant appreciations. I\n&gt; will be glad to answer provided with Grace and Blessings of The\n&gt; Ever-Existing Aatma in the form Shri Gurudeva.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]* *Sun\n&gt; 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:]*\n&gt;\n&gt; 1) Why does Aatma exist ?\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Kannan:] *Let me do its mimaansa(analysis). Let me assume that your\n&gt; question is valid, and hence assume that there does exist a valid answer.\n&gt; Consider Event A : &quot;aatma exist&quot;\n&gt; Consider Event B : &quot;reasons or cause for event A&quot;.\n&gt; If your answer is assumed to be existing, then event B must precede event\n&gt; A. In other words, event A cannot occur, unless and until event B has\n&gt; occurred.\n&gt; Now, if your question is assumed to be a valid one, then event B must also\n&gt; cannot be stand-alone entity, but has to be supported by another preceding\n&gt; event C.\n&gt; Again, assuming your question to be valid and re-applied to event C, it\n&gt; must have another precedence event D..and so on..till infinite endless loop.\n&gt; In mathematics, whenever we encounter, infinite loops or forms, we call it\n&gt; &quot;indeterminate&quot; or &quot;undefined&quot; like even in computer science you have this\n&gt; concept. It&#39;s a hang-up.\n&gt;\n&gt; So it is clear that answer to your question does not exist\n&gt; deterministically. In such case, the question becomes invalid.\n&gt;\n&gt; Now why this invalidity is occurring for a simple question? Because, the\n&gt; question is valid only in domain of &quot;cause-effect&quot; linearity or\n&gt; circularity. In such cases, you always have a preceding point for a given\n&gt; point. Aatma is beyond all space, time, cause, effect etc. So you cannot\n&gt; apply this principle of &quot;cause-effect&quot; to Aatma which itself is beyond this\n&gt; frame of reference.\n&gt;\n&gt; In other words, you cannot discuss or understand Aatma logically like what\n&gt; we do to other entities in day-to-day life.\n&gt;\n&gt; Forget about Aatma, take a very simple logical infinity loop, which fails\n&gt; miserably to attain a stable logical state. I give you that example as\n&gt; follows:\n&gt;  In logic or propositional calculus, a line is called &quot;statement&quot;, if it\n&gt; attains either a &quot;Truth value&quot;(Binary 1) or a &quot;False value&quot;(Binary 0).But\n&gt; not both simultanesouly, of course.\n&gt;\n&gt; Can you imagine a line which never attains any of the truth or false\n&gt; value, but keeps oscillating or shuttling between them? Well, let me share\n&gt; it.\n&gt; A person says :&quot; I always speak lies.&quot; Now, in logic, this is not called a\n&gt; statement because it has no stable truth value or stable false value. How?\n&gt; let me explain.\n&gt;\n&gt; If the above line is true, then whatever he says is false(as he always\n&gt; speaks lies). If whatever he says is false, then whatever he said must be\n&gt; true.(because he said that he always speak lies, and this is false, so he\n&gt; must be speaking truth.)\n&gt;\n&gt; Puzzling? Well, this is called infinite loop or oscillation. The line &quot;I\n&gt; always speak lies&quot;, hence as per rules of propositional calculus, is not a\n&gt; logical statement. So, logic fails miserably even in a mere line, then how\n&gt; it can help us in defining or understanding Aatma?\n&gt;\n&gt; So the bottomline is, Aatma is neither discussed nor explained nor\n&gt; logically verified, rather it is realized. And one more thing, you cannot\n&gt; apply the condition of &quot;cause-effect&quot; to one who is beyond all this. And\n&gt; your question, is a typical &quot;cause-effect&quot; one; which violates head-on the\n&gt; very definition of Aatma as one beyond all cause-effect, space, time etc.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]* *Sun\n&gt; 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:]*\n&gt;\n&gt; 2) Why does Aatma has this center of desire ? Who created it ?\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Kannan:] *The answer is almost similar to what I discussed in the\n&gt; preceding question. Still I summarise here, Aatma by definition has Chitta,\n&gt; and none has created it. It is its very nature. And Chitta also exist\n&gt; eternally. Anything which is created will be dismantled or destroyed. Aatma\n&gt; is beyond any creation or destruction.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]* *Sun\n&gt; 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:]*\n&gt;\n&gt; 3) Does a rock has Aatma too ? Do plants have Aatma too ?\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Kannan:] *Yes. They all are Aatma in various forms, with various levels\n&gt; of consciousness trapped between the lowliest level to the highest level.\n&gt; Whatever we perceive through senses, and whatever we do not perceive while\n&gt; asleep, everything is Aatma only. One who realizes this gets freed from all\n&gt; sorrows, and stays in Stitha-Pragnya Awastha as Shri Krushna mentioned in\n&gt; Shrimadh-Bhagawat-geet-opanishadam.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]* *Sun\n&gt; 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:]*\n&gt;\n&gt; 4) Why is this information (mentioned in the five points above) not easily\n&gt; visible or experienced or felt ?\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Kannan:] *I am very happy to hear penetrative questions from you. Your\n&gt; eagerness to know energizes me to answer you. Let me give you few examples.\n&gt; Suppose I look down upon a still water filled with mud. Will I be able to\n&gt; see my face? No. The mud creates a block in the water to reflect image\n&gt; clearly.\n&gt; But if I look down upon a clean and still water, Will I be able to see my\n&gt; face? Yes. Because the water is in its true form to reflect.\n&gt; So, why my face is not easily visible or experienced or felt in a muddy\n&gt; water? Because of the mud polluting the water. Right? Fine.\n&gt;\n&gt; Now, likewise, if manas(mind) is very busy or turbulent in engaging itself\n&gt; in various outward activities of the 10 indriyas(5 sense and 5 action\n&gt; organs), then such Ahankaara-chitta-buddhi-manas combo called jeevaatmaa is\n&gt; said to be having a muddy water in an unstable, excited ever-active mind.\n&gt; In other words, the outward orientation of mind is equivalent to a muddy\n&gt; water.\n&gt; Under such extrovertness or bahir-mukhi-awastha, one cannot realize Aatma\n&gt; and it remains forever invisible, un-experienced and un-felt.\n&gt;\n&gt; So here is where the secret of All Saadhana lies. Which I cannot discuss\n&gt; now as the post is getting lengthy.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]* *Sun\n&gt; 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:]*\n&gt;\n&gt; 5) How to know that what you have written is true ?\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Kannan:] *J..The answer is sweet and simple. By realizing Aatma,\n&gt; through quieting one&#39;s mind. In Bible it is written &quot;Be Still, And Know\n&gt; That I Am God&quot;. This is the key. &quot;Be Still&quot;. &quot;Be Quiet&quot;. It&#39;s a mere two\n&gt; words, but it will require pages to explain it and explore it. Once\n&gt; ArunagiriNathar asked Shri Kaarthikeya to utter some knowledge of Aatma.\n&gt; Shri Shanmuga answered -\n&gt; &quot;Summaa Iru&quot;. Means &quot;Be Quiet&quot;. Shri Dakshinamurthy Shiva is a 16 year old\n&gt; Gurudeva, and who never utters anything, but all knowledge is understood\n&gt; and Aatma is realized just being with him for a while. He is truly called\n&gt; &quot;Mauna-Guru&quot;.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Phil Stinnet [philstinnet@... &lt;philstinnet@...&gt;]* *Sun\n&gt; 3/16/2014 2:23 AM:]*\n&gt;\n&gt; Thanks a lot. It will be really helpful if you can answer these. I have\n&gt; more questions. But, i will ask them later.\n&gt;\n&gt; *[Kannan:] *You are very welcome. It is my utmost pleasure to get the\n&gt; opportunity to share my experience with your noble self. It is you who are\n&gt; doing me a favor by giving me an opportunity to serve you, and accepting my\n&gt; humble service with  pleasure, happiness, peace, satisfaction and\n&gt; blessings, neglecting/ignoring the inherent flaws. This is verily a\n&gt; blessing for me, as My Ishwara is pleased with me and has come in your form\n&gt; to accept my offerings. I was roaming like an animal, and He showered His\n&gt; Grace and Love and Mercy, and now again He has showered me with His Benign\n&gt; Looks, as He comes in your form to accept my offerings. I seek Bhakti at\n&gt; His Holy Feet and nothing else. May He Bless All of us with Bhakti at His\n&gt; Lotus-Like Holy Feet.\n&gt;\n&gt; I have truly expressed my heart&#39;s words. And it is not a jugglery of\n&gt; high-sounding words, but a genuine voice of heart coming out like flowers\n&gt; and reaching the Holy Feet of My Beloved Ishwara. You are always welcome\n&gt; for any number of questions, and I always consider it as a worship to my\n&gt; Ishwara while I answer them.\n&gt;\n&gt; Let us conclude with a Tribute to the Aatma.\n&gt; Aum Poornam-adah Poornam-idam Poornaat-Poornam-udachyatey\n&gt; Poorn-asya Poornam-aadaaya Poornam-evaavashishyatey\n&gt;\n&gt; Meaning, That is Full, This is Full, From That Full comes This Full,\n&gt;                 From This Full, remove That Full, what indeed remains is\n&gt; That Full.\n&gt;\n&gt; Aum Shaantih Shaantih Shaantih\n&gt;\n&gt; With Kind Regards,\n&gt; Kannan\n&gt;\n